LayerData.variable: Hello, Thanks for trying out VNOS. This mail was collected with a script embedded in a TCP port widget hidden behind the word "VNOS" at the bottom of this panel. To view the script, Option double-click the word "VNOS" below. This will open the TCP port's properties panel. Click on the Script tab to open the script window for the TCP port. You will find the code for interacting with the objects on this panel and a mail server. Lone Wolf

VNOS - This is the root of all views.
The VNOS view also contains other Standard Views such as:
Notepad - The notepad window is for taking quick notes and jotting down ideas and thoughts.
Objects Inventory - Contains the available Widgets.
Utility - The Utility View contains views and widgets for various helpful tasks. Standard Utility functions include: Script Exporter and Time View.
System - The System View contains system specific widgets and applications.

%7F%7Fclass: a reference to a Vnos Class instance: a reference to a Vnos Object variable: a reference to one of many Vnos Variables contained in a Vnos Object view: a reference to a Vnos View instance vref: a reference to a visual element in a Vnos View container: instance of a Container type Class, e.g. Class and View
lParam, wParam: generic Vnos Message parameters: see specific messages for meanings string, number: data types msg: Vnos message ID
'word: execution address of a word ( use the syntax "' word" to get this from the command line, or "%5B'%5D word" to get it inside a definition)

Declaration ----------- String x ( size -- ) Declare string named x with size -1 from the heap.
Manipulation ------------ StrCat ( s1 s2 -- ) append s1 to s2 StrCpy ( s1 s2 -- ) copy s1 onto s2 StrLen ( s -- n ) length of string s StrForm ( n format str -- ) format n into str using format according to sprintf rules
Extracting ---------- StrInt ( s1 -- s1' n ) convert head of s1 into number n, also leave ptr to next char StrReal ( s1 -- s2 f ) StrLine ( s1 s2 n -- n | 0 ) extract first line from s1 into s2 max length n, leave actual n. SubStr ( s1 start len s2 -- ) extract len chars from s1%5Bstart%5D into s2 StrTok ( start s1 s2 -- end ) copy first token from s1%5Bstart%5D into s2, leave end offset any non-alphameric character is a token/separator, you'll see them all StrToken ( s1 s2 -- s1' ) copy first token from s1 into s2, leaving ptr to next part of s1 tokens are bounded by whitespace, may only contain whitespace if in ".." or '..' escapes such as \r are converted
Searching (1) ------------- StrChar ( s1 s2 -- s3 | 0 ) Find 1st occurance of *s2 in s1%03, no match = 0 else new StrPtr. StrCmp ( s1 s2 -- -1 | 0 | 1 ) comapre strings StrCmpI ( s1 s2 -- -1 | 0 | 1 ) case-insensitive compare strings
Searching (2) ------------ The following words are case-agile according to the settings done by one of: Case_insensitive ( -- ) turns off case sensitivity Case_sensitive ( -- ) turns on case sensitivity Set_Case_Mode ( n -- ) sets sensitivity on or off Get_Case_Mode ( -- n ) test current setting
StrInList ( s1 slist -- index ) find s1 in the list of strings slist, leave index or -1 slist is an array of pointers to strings, with a NULL pointer at the end StrFind ( s1 s2 -- s2' | 0 ) find the first occurrence of s1 as a substring of s2 leave a pointer to the next un-matched character in s2, or NULL if not found StrHead ( s1 s2 -- s2' ) see if s1 matches the start of s2, leave ptr to next char in s2

Once you have a struct defined, you can spawn off data blobs as instances of the struct type:
CreateStructInstace ( sdef -- pData )
You can discover the positions of the data elements within pData and access them using combinations of the words:
FieldByName ( name sdef -- fdef ) FieldOffset ( fdef -- offset ) FieldSize ( fdef -- size )
So, for the example, you could, assuming the struct definition was in a Text Control called StructDef,:
variable sdef StructDef.var v@" CreateStructDefinition sdef ! "name" sdef @ FieldByname FieldOffset constant MyStruct.name "age" sdef @ FieldByname FieldOffset constant MyStruct.age ... variable pData sdef @ CreateStructInstance pData ! ... "David" pData @ MyStruct.name + strcpy 51 pData @ MyStruct.age + !
If all you have is a pData, and want the "name" value, you can:
pData @ dup StructOfInstance "name" swap FieldByName FieldOffset +
to get a pointer to the name field.

A Data Structure can be defined either programmatically or via a text string.
The programmatic method allows one to construct structures based upon current circumstances. The words used here are:
CreateStruct ( name -- sdef ) AddField ( name type sdef -- fdef ) AddArray ( dim name type sdef -- fdef ) SetFieldFormat ( fstring fdef -- )
For example,
"MyStruct" CreateStruct 32 "name" ST_STRING 3 pick AddArray "%25s" swap SetFieldFormat "age" ST_INT 2 pick AddField "%25d" swap SetFieldFormat
This leaves sdef on the stack.
The string method allows one to include structure definitions from external sources, such as files, HTML streams, resources, VNOS Text Objects, etc. The syntax is very simple:
struct %3Cname%3E {%3Ctype%3E name %5Bdim %3Cn%3E%5D %5Bformat %3Cstring%3E%5D %5Bendian %3C0|1%3E%5D} endstruct
Here, dim specifies an array of type, format specifies how to render the element into text, and endian is useful for parsing binary blobs of data received from another machine. For example,
struct MyStruct string name dim 32 format "%25s" int age format "%25d" endstruct
Given as the argument to CompileStructDefinition, would yield the same sdef as the programmatic example

VNOS introduces several complex data types and a comprehensive vocabulary for manipulating them:
Structure: a simple syntax is used to create structured data blobs Database: fast in-RAM with sort and search facilities Structured Database: database with structure definitions for their records Treebase: tree structures with a typed name/value pair at each node
Structured Datases and Treebases also offer persistence.

The URL Cracker is used without scripting to generate the inputs to the TCP Port. Press ctrl to see the connects.
Opt-DblClick the TCP Port Icon and select the Scripts Tab, then Vnos Object Script Part to see all the scripting this took.
The URL Cracker spits out the socket number last, so this Event is used to kick things off. When the data has been received, the RxReady Event is used to extract the title into Document Title.
Note that this View is where all the Original References were placed, so the name DocumentTitle.var would be visible to the TCP Port script.

MyVScript ( -- instance ) gets a reference to the invoked VScript
these two do not coerce the data type; the type is appropriate to the Variable's style and may therefore be either String or Number.

These words affect the message passing and propagation.

The VScript class implements both the CVScript Objects and the CVScriptor intercept script property Objects.
The CVScript implements a convenient, closely-bound container of 10 scriptable Variables with a common Code Page. The VScript Panel (single-clisk on the VScript Icon) has the ten prototypes for these Variables plus four other buttons:
Show Console opens an interactive Forth Console for the VScript Object. Each VScript has its own Console, but access the common Forth Vocabulary defined by all Scripts.
Code Page opens the general Code Page Scrit for the Object. This is intended for writing Forth words as utilities for the functionality you desire the Object to implement other than the value change events themselves.
Enable is a system-wide Scripting Enable control. It is duplicated on each VScript Panel for convenience, as well as on every Cmd-J Scipts Tab.
Compile System is also a system-wide button duplicated here and on Script Tabs for convenience.l You must compile the system for any changes you make to Scripts to be activated.
Each of the Variables has a Change Event word that can be written. Access to this code is by Cmd-Double-click on the variable's control in the main VScript Panel. The code itself must implement a single Forth word, AND MUST OMIT THE LEADING ': %3Cname%3E' AND CLOSING ':' definition parts - these are constructed for you by the compilation process. The word must assume no stack input and leave no stack change on return. See VScript Words for more info. This word will be invoked whenever there is a user input or connected Message Event.
The common Code Page contains conventional Forth code, and is compiled before the individual change code scripts.
Each of the 10 Variables has a symbol %3Cname%3E defined for it.
You can use Opt-DblClk to edit the properties of each Variable, including its name and style. Note that the VScriptor Property is independant of and in addition to the built-in scripting of the VSCript Object itself. Browse the example below. The Start and Tally buttons have Change Scripts attatched.
UpdateMe GetChangeValue if "Allowed" else "Inhibited" then Status V!"
Start v@ if Total v@ Increment v@ + Total v! Total v@ Threshold v@ %3E= if -1 EventColor v@ else 1 0 then OutputEvent v! Increment v! then
There are only a few Classes one need be aware of in Vnos for scripting purposes
CObject is the root Class from which all other Classes descend.
CClass provides Class behaviour, e.g. New, DefaultMsg, etc.
CUserView handles presentation of the Visual aspects of Vnos Objects in a Desktop Window.
Icons and Controls visible in a View are managed by the CViewRefObject Class.
All computational Objects (i.e. those in the Objects Inventory) are subclasses of CNetworkDevice
Not truly a Class, these are contained in CNetworkDevices. They are associated with data entry or display Controls. These are the things that pass messages around via connections.

VScript generates a number of labels for the Objects in the Environment. It does this in a way that provides for a natural 'scoping' of names with respect to the code added to an Object or its Variables. Names are always derived from the name you see on the screen by removing all characters except alpha-numerics and the '.'. Since VScript is Forth-based, so does not allow forward references, it is important to know the order in which labels and code are generated. That order is:
1: the file startup.VScript in the VNOS folder is executed at program load only. Everything else is compiled whenever you load an Environment or click on a "Compile System" Property or VScript button.
2: All loaded Classes are given names. You might use these, e.g., as in "A New View" 0 CUserView New which will create a new View and leave its reference on the stack
3: Constant names are generated for Variable ID's for all CNetworkDevice subclasses loaded. These are constructed as %3Cdemoname%3E.%3Cvariablesymbol%3E, e.g. the demo CTimer Object is called %5BTimer%5D, so its ID symbols after stripping special chars will be things like Timer.Output, Timer.Timebase, Timer.Enable, Timer.Start. You would use these, e.g., to get access to the Variables of an Object Instance for which you got the reference at run time.
4: The demo VScript Object /Objects Inventory/%5BVScript%5D is compiled.
5: Starting at /, a PreOrderVisit tree-walk is made through the Views heirarchy. For each View that is found to contain at least one VScripted Object, 6 thru 12 are performed. Be aware that only "original" Objects are considered, i.e. the first reference (usually an Icon or Solo Control) was placed on that View.
6: Each CViewRefObject get the name %3Cname%3E.ref. This leaves the CViewRefObject reference on the stack.
7: Each original gets the name %3Cname%3E, which leaves the CNetworkDevice or CUserView reference on the stack.
8: Each Control gets the name %3Cname%3E.var, which leaves the Vnos Variable reference on the stack, i.e. the reference you need for V@ and V! etc.
9: The Views' CVScriptor Object is compiled.
10: all original CVScript Objects are compiled.
11: all original CNetworkDevice Onjects with attatched CVScriptor scripts are compiled. For each Variable in the Object, a word %3Clabel%3E.var is defined, where %3Clabel%3E is what you see on the Panel with spaces and funny characters removed.
12: all CViewRefObjects with CVScriptors are compiled.

LayerData.variable:
It may often be required that the TaskData parameter be the address of a data structure, and further that you may need to allocate this dynamically. When your State Machine terminates, you will therefore need to free up these resources. This is accomplished by defining a word that does so, e.g.
: FreeTaskData TaskData free ;
and then, from inside your first state word, execute
... StructSize Alloc SetTaskData %5B'%5D FreeTaskData DyingWord ...
This word will now get called when the State Machine terminates, for whatever reason.

instance.path: /VNOS Reference/VScript Tutorial/State Machines/Inside a Task/Timed Execution/TheText

LayerData.variable:
You can control the timing of the execution with the syntax:
SleepTask ( will put the task to sleep indefinitely ) n Seconds Delay ( will sleep for n seconds )
By default, if you do not do one of these, the word will be run as fast as the system allows. After waking from a sleep, it will again be running full speed.

instance.path: /VNOS Reference/VScript Tutorial/State Machines/Inside a Task/Cyclic Execution/TheText

LayerData.variable:
State Machines are usually cyclic; this implies there will be at least one forward reference. VScript does not accept these directly, but there is an indirect way of doing this with the syntax:
( indirection place-holder for the forward reference) defer anotherWord ( a forward reference ) : aWord %5B'%5D anotherWord NextState ; ( not a forward reference ) : anotherWordDeferred %5B'%5D aWord NextState ; ( resolve the forward reference ) ' anotherWordDeferred is anotherWord
See the VScriptor in the Example for this usage.

instance.path: /VNOS Reference/VScript Tutorial/State Machines/Inside a Task/Sequential Execution/TheText

LayerData.variable:
State machines have a useful characteristic: they traverse states. The idea behind this implementation is that you write a word for each state of your machine. In each word, you process the current state, determine if there is to be a state transition, and if so make the transition using the syntax:
%5B'%5D anotherWord NextState
If your code should do this more than once in an execution, the last one executed will be the one that determines the next word to be executed.

instance.path: /VNOS Reference/VScript Tutorial/State Machines/Inside a Task/Run Time Parameters/TheText

LayerData.variable:
Inside aWord, you can get at the two parameters passed to RunWord (Self and parameter in the example) with the words
TaskInstance ( -- Self ) TaskData ( -- parameter )
You can also change the parameter value with:
SetTaskData ( data -- )

instance.path: /VNOS Reference/VScript Tutorial/State Machines/State Machine Words/State Machine QuickRef/TheText

LayerData.variable:
State Machine words
CreateTask ( ^instance param 'word -- task ) RunTask ( ^instance param 'word -- task ) ( RunWord ) DyingWord ( 'word -- )
---
Wake ( -- ) wakes up the current task (most useful inside an ANR word) NextState ( 'word -- ) alias to NextWord Delay ( delay -- ) delays the next execution of the current task Sleep ( -- ) puts the current task to sleep EndStates ( -- ) current Task terminates when the task word completes ( same as "0 NextState")
TaskID ( -- myID )
----------
WakeTask ( task -- ) wakes up task ( ST_Sleep Sleep ) DelayTask ( delay task -- ) delays task (taskid @ SleepTask ) SleepTask ( task -- ) and puts task to sleep ( n taskid @ SleepTask ) KillTask ( task -- )

To start a word running, use the syntax (assuming this code is inside a word definition):
variable taskId Self parameter %5B'%5D aWord RunTask theTaskId !
taskId is useful later on from outside the running word to do things to it, e.g.:
taskId @ KillTask ( to terminate it )
There is one word you may need to use while developing State machines:
KillAllVTasks - will terminate all running VScripted state machines.

A Word can be defined to be executed repeatedly under control of the VNOS State machine engine. One can change the word to be executed next from within the running word, one can delay execution for a specified time, and one can "tickle" such a machine to wake up and continue running, or to die.
A State Machine word has only one real rule: it must obey the stack picture ( -- ) or bad things will happen. This is the same restriction as intercept words, so you should be familiar with it.
Two generic items of context are available to a running word. By convention, one is usually an instance reference (typically Self of the invoker).
The word(s) also enjoy all the normal contextual definitions that the others in its script get at compile time, but not at run time (e.g. Self and SelfVar cannot be used).
A special State Machine Context is created for each RunTask use. This contains the generic parameters, the word to be executed next, the DyingWord, the AnrWord, and various other information. You can assume that the current context belongs to the State run word or anr word (or any it called directly ...) at time of execution.

VScript includes a vocabulary that implements a simple yet powerful State Machine system. This is useful for scripting applications such as: protocol parsers, Event Recognizers, user interaction progress, etc.
State Machines can be thought of also as a kind of sub-routine or service that executes independantly of the caller; the VScript vocabulary allows one State Machne to call on the services of another, and to be notified of the callee's progress and results in an asynchronous manner. (One might call such a service machine a "Sub-Machine" :-)
Scripting, while powerful, is not necessarily fast. Sometimes one has a long task to execute. It is good practice then to break the processing up into some number of sequential states. This will allow other scripts and VNOS tasks time to execute in an inter-leaved manner.

When your VScriptor intercept code is invoked, you have access to several variables that give you information about the message and the execution environment. In general, the semantics of these depend both upon the Class of the Object to which you are attatched, and the message you are intercepting. We introduce the variables here, but go to the message-specific discussions below for more details.
VScriptor maintains a nested list of execution environments. It creates a new one at the start of an intercept, and fills it in with the generic parameters from the message and a reference to the Object receiving the message. The words defined in "VScriptor Words" References and Parameters show how to access and/or change these. Once an intercept has been invoked for a message, the normal processing for that message will not occur unless and until you explicitly issue the command "DefaultMsg". This gives you fine control over when and how the defauot happens. For instance, you may want to modify the message parameters, or intercept only certain cases, or completely replace the normal behaviour.

Every Object in Vnos has provisions for installing Vnos Message Intercept scripts, in any installed language. VScriptor is one such language. To access the Scripts property for any Object you can click on via the Scripts Tab on its Cmd-J Editor.
The Controls you will see there have the following purposes:
Compile Scripts: this button does the same thing regardless of what Panel you find it on: it re-compiles ALL VScript and VScriptor Scripts. A Console will pop up if any errors are encountered.
Enable Scripting: another universal control: if Off, VScriptor scripts will not be executed.
Show Console: pops up the %5BVScript%5D demo console so you can interact with the interpreter.
Enabled: Enable/Disable VScriptor code on this Object only.
Script Part: select which Object to atatch Script to: either the View Alias or the Vnos Object. The View Alias means that the Script will be attatched to the ViewRefObj - the visual element you clicked on. This will allow you to intercept mouse clicks and pother User interaction, but not Vnos messages passed to the underlying Object. For that, select and edit the Vnos Object Script. Note that the compile and execution environment of the View Alias is the View it is in, while that of the Vnos Object is the View containing its Original Reference. These might not be the same.
Script Type: select the language for the Script Part. Note that selecting "No Script" will discard any script previously present.

TRACE ( n -- ) turns execution tracing on and off; 0 is off, 1 is trace while running, 2 is single-step.
Once stepping, space will step over nested definitions, return will step into them. g turns of tracing and continues, Esc aborts and turns off trasing.
WORDTRACE ( 'word truth -- ) trace entry into a word (truth = True ) or turn it off WORDBREAK ( 'word truth -- ) enter 2 trace mode on entry ( TRUE) or turn it off
WORDSMARKED ( -- ) list all words with WORDTRACE or WORDBREAK set
FORGET ( w : -- ) forget the word w. If w does not exist or is below the PROTECTED boundary it will fail with a warning.
?FORGET ( w : -- ) like FORGET, but fails quietly
PROTECTED ( 'word -- ) marks the word 'word as the PROTECTED boundary
WARNINGLEVEL ( N -- oldN ) sets the warning level for redefinition of words. 0: never warn 1: warn only if word being redefined is protected 2: warn if any word is redefined
RECURSIVE ( n -- ) affects the behaviour when a word references its own name in its definition. If n is 0, then it will look up a prior definition. If n is 1, then it will resolve the address to itself.

WORDS ( -- ) lists all words in the dictionary. This is not very useful, as there are so many!
NWORDS ( n -- ) lists the most recent n words in the dictionary
INWORDS ( string -- ) lists all words containing string anywhere
If you follow the convention of putting a stack picture comment immediately after the word, on the same line, the VScript will store that with the definition. You can see it if ShowHelp is 1. Set this:
1 ShowHelp ! ( sets long listing ) 0 ShowHelp ! ( turns it off )
If you want to include a longer help string instead, then immediately after the definition closes use the syntax:
"a longer and more informative help string" HelpString
You can add help strings after the fact using the syntax:
SetHelpString ( string 'word -- )

VScript is a Forth-like scripting language for Vnos Objects and Events. Any and every aspect of normal Vnos operations can be intercepted, over-ridden, or controlled, via suitably placed VScript Objects or VScriptor Properties.

Objects in the "Objects Inventory" cannot be deleted but they may be configured with default values so that any copies that you create by dragging them out into another view will carry with them the settings from the template object they were cloned from.
All highlighted objects will receive any command that is issued.

This is a demo of how one might implement a shifting value.
Every VU, Button, and Fader has a simple script behind it. The support words are behind the Play View itself.
Note that the stimulus input is from the left, while the value input and flow is from the right.
The VU and Fader scriipts call a word that disables value propagation from them. This would not be necessary if we had a UI to the connection flags. They also intercept OnChange and deliberately do not call defaultMsg so that anything coming in to them (i.e. from the Buttons) does not disturb their value. This would also be unneccesary once we get the Connection Flags UI implemented. Note that the Fader does a DefaultMsg while the VUs do not. This is because the Fader must get its own value, while the VUs are set by the Button scripts.
